{
  "answer": "Revised stance and design: A blanket, broad tax on automation should not be pursued as a stand‑alone solution. Evidence on displacement is mixed and context‑specific; macro effects depend on country characteristics, sector mix, and the design of policy instruments. If a policy instrument addressing automation is considered, it should be narrowly targeted, time‑limited, and paired with strong evaluation to avoid chilling investment, misallocating capital, or harming productivity. The proposal below outlines a rigorous framework to move from principle to practice.\n\n1) Clear definition and measurement of automation\n- Adopt a transparent taxonomy that combines robotics hardware, software that substitutes routine tasks, and process automation tools. Define automation intensity as the share of tasks carried out by automated means, measured with firm‑level data on automation investments, deployment of robotics and RPA, and software automation usage.\n- Use standardized measurement approaches (aligned with OECD/ISO-like frameworks) to ensure cross‑jurisdiction comparability. Collect data through mandatory annual reporting and secure surveys, with privacy protections and audit trails.\n- Predefine boundary conditions to avoid vagueness: include only investments that substitute human labor in core production or service delivery processes; exclude purely digital optimizations that do not substitute tasks in labor markets.\n\n2) Tax base design and avoidance risk management\n- If a tax or levy is considered, base it on observable automation investments with clearly defined depreciation rules and rate bands, designed to minimize gaming (front‑loading, recharacterization).\n- Build in robust compliance infrastructure, third‑party verification, and transparent reporting to reduce evasion. Treat exemptions and transitional relief as explicit, time‑bound, and tied to objective criteria (e.g., meaningful hardship, sectoral adjustment needs).\n- Ensure the instrument is revenue‑recycling: allocate proceeds to worker retraining, wage subsidies, portable benefits, and productivity‑enhancing public investments. Prohibit revenue diversion to unrelated budgets.\n\n3) Pilot design, evaluation, and decision rules\n- Implement pilot programs before scale, using quasi‑experimental designs (difference‑in‑differences, synthetic controls) or randomized rollout where feasible.\n- Key evaluation metrics: displacement rate by sector, uptake of retraining, wage trajectories, productivity, investment responses, and net tax/levy revenue; include macroeconomic counterfactuals in the analysis.\n- Sample size and duration: select multiple jurisdictions with varying income levels and sector mixes; run pilots for 3–5 years with interim assessments and a final comprehensive evaluation.\n- Publish evaluation results and ensure counterfactuals are credible before any scale‑up or extension.\n\n4) Time bounds, governance, and sunset rules\n- Any instrument should include explicit sunset clauses (e.g., 5–7 years) with renewal criteria tied to performance benchmarks and evaluation findings. Establish governance criteria to ensure independence of evaluation and to prevent creeping expansion.\n\n5) International coordination and enforcement\n- Engage in credible international coordination to minimize avoidance, legitimate cross‑border arbitrage, and inconsistent definitions. Align measurement standards, information sharing, and audit capabilities, with clear timelines and enforcement mechanisms.\n\n6) Complementary policy framework\n- Emphasize policies with stronger empirical support for reducing displacement with less risk to productivity: high‑quality retraining, wage subsidies, portable benefits, employment protection where necessary, and policies that foster human–robot collaboration. Tailor these to country, sector, and firm size considerations; avoid overreliance on a single instrument.\n\n7) Incidence and distributional analysis\n- Develop explicit models to understand who bears the costs and who gains, including potential wage, price, and productivity channels. Use the models to inform exemptions, transfer design, and revenue recycling. Build in safeguards for workers most at risk of displacement.\n\nIn sum, if automation policy is pursued, it should be narrowly targeted, evidence‑driven, transparently measured, and rigorously evaluated. The preferred stance remains to rely on complementary policies that support workers and firms rather than a broad tax; a narrowly designed, well‑evaluated instrument could be considered only as part of a broader policy mix, not as a stand‑alone solution.",
